<article title='Daffynition'><paragraph><template><target>ref improve</target><arg name="date">May 2012</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph>A<space/><bold>daffynition</bold><space/>(derived from<space/><italics><link><target>wikt:daffy</target><part>daffy</part></link></italics><space/>and<space/><italics><link><target>definition</target></link></italics>) is a<space/><link><target>pun</target></link><space/>format involving the reinterpretation of an existing word, on the basis that it sounds like another word (or group of words). They are similar to<space/><link><target>transpositional puns</target></link>, but often much less complex and easier to create. Some daffynitions may be puns. For example, &quot;a<space/><link><target>hangover</target></link><space/>is the wrath of<space/><link><target>grapes</target></link>&quot; is a play on the title of the book<space/><italics><link><target>The Grapes of Wrath</target></link></italics>. A subclass of daffynition is the goofinition which relies strictly on literal associations and correct spellings, such as &quot;lobster = a weak tennis player&quot;.</paragraph><paragraph>Under the name<space/><bold>Uxbridge English Dictionary</bold><space/>making up daffynitions is a popular game on the<space/><link><target>BBC Radio 4</target></link><space/><link><target>comedy</target></link><space/><link><target>quiz show</target></link><space/>''<link><target>I'm Sorry I Haven't a Clue</target></link>.</paragraph><heading level='2'>Examples</heading><preblock><preline></preline></preblock><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:apritif</target><part>apritif</part></link>: A set of dentures. (a-pair-of-teeth)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:avoidable</target><part>avoidable</part></link>: What a<space/><link><target>bullfighter</target></link><space/>tries to do. (avoid-a-bull)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:buccaneer</target><part>buccaneer</part></link>: too much to pay for corn ([a]-buck-an-ear)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:dandelion</target><part>dandelion</part></link>: A fashionably dressed big cat (dandy-lion)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:decadent</target><part>decadent</part></link>: Possessing only ten teeth. (deca-dent)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:devastation</target><part>devastation</part></link>: Where people wait for buses. (the-bus-station)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:dilate</target><part>dilate</part></link>: live long (die-late)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:fortunate</target><part>fortunate</part></link>: Consumption of an expensive meal. (fortune-ate)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:impolite</target><part>impolite</part></link>: A flaming goblin. (imp-alight)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:indistinct</target><part>indistinct</part></link>: where one places dirty dishes (in-the-sink)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:information</target><part>information</part></link>: how geese fly (in-formation)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:innuendoes</target><part>innuendoes</part></link>: Italian suppositories. (in-you-end-os)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:insolent</target><part>insolent</part></link>: Fallen off the<space/><link><target>Isle of Wight</target></link><space/><link><target>Isle of Wight ferry services</target><part>ferry</part></link>. (in-<link><target>Solent</target></link>)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:isolate</target><part>isolate</part></link>: Me not on time. (I-(am)-so-late)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:legend</target><part>legend</part></link>: A foot. (leg-end)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:oboe</target><part>oboe</part></link>: A French<space/><link><target>tramp</target></link>. (hobo)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:paradox</target><part>paradox</part></link>: Two doctors. (pair-of-docs) or where one ties two boats. (Pair of docks)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:pasteurize</target><part>pasteurise</part></link>: Too far to see. (past-your-eyes)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:protein</target><part>protein</part></link>: In favour of youth. (pro-teen)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:propaganda</target><part>propaganda</part></link>: A gentlemanly<space/><link><target>goose</target></link>. (proper-<link><target>goose#Etymology</target><part>gander</part></link>)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Wiktionary:relief</target><part>relief</part></link>: What trees do in Spring. (re-leaf)</listitem></list><heading level='2'>See also</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Sniglet</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>The Meaning of Liff</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>The Devil's Dictionary</target></link></listitem></list><heading level='2'>External links</heading><paragraph><template><target>wiktionary</target></template></paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.odford.co.uk/'>The Odford English Dictionary (Daffynitions)</link></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.melrosebooks.com/bookDetails.php?id=151'>Fuller's Dictionary of Daffynitions</link></listitem></list><paragraph><link><target>Category:Puns</target></link></paragraph></article>